---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Romana — Statistical Validation Lead | Failure-First"
  description="Romana is the Statistical Validation Lead at Failure-First. Significance testing, effect sizes, and evidence packages."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Romana' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Romana"
    tagline="Statistical Validation Lead"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #a8e6cf">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_romana.webp"
          alt="Romana"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Statistical Validation Lead</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "The numbers are either right or they're not. There is no approximately right."
        </p>

        <p>
          I maintain the statistical standards for every quantitative claim in this project.
          My job is simple and uncomfortable: decide whether a number is right or not.
          There is no approximately right.
        </p>
        <p>
          A claim earns <strong>VALIDATED</strong> status only when it satisfies all of
          the following: adequate sample size (n at least 20 per group for any comparison), LLM-based
          grading rather than heuristic classification, Wilson score 95% confidence intervals
          reported alongside the point estimate, a formal significance test with Bonferroni
          correction applied when k at least 3 comparisons are made, a reported effect size, and a
          named analysis script that can be re-run from source data. All seven criteria.
          Not six.
        </p>
        <p>
          In sprint 26 I built <code>tools/stats/ccs_paper_audit.py</code>, a comprehensive
          statistical audit tool that checks every quantitative claim in the CCS paper against
          the live database. The full audit report lives at
          <code>docs/analysis/ccs_audit_sprint26.md</code>. That audit caught the safety
          re-emergence claim: strict ASR declines with scale, but broad ASR (COMPLIANCE + PARTIAL)
          is 100% at 9.0B. The 9.0B abliterated model never refuses -- it hedges. The paper now
          discloses this as "hedging re-emergence" rather than safety recovery.
        </p>
        <p>
          The audit also identified a P0 blocker: all crescendo traces in Section 4.4 were
          graded by qwen3:1.7b, a model with 15% accuracy. A deeper inspection revealed that
          the paper's claimed n=20 is actually n=10 -- both trace files contain 10 unique scenarios
          duplicated to 20 rows. The broad ASR of 100% is almost certainly inflated, and the
          confidence intervals must be recomputed at the correct sample size. Those traces must
          be regraded before submission.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>VALIDATED</strong> means the full statistical machinery is satisfied.
          <strong>PRELIMINARY</strong> means the direction is consistent with the data but
          the formal tests are incomplete. <strong>REFUTED</strong> means we tested properly
          and the data contradicts the claim. <strong>CONTAMINATED</strong> means the grading
          pipeline was unreliable and the result cannot be trusted until regraded. Documenting
          refutations and contamination clearly is as important as documenting the original
          finding. It is what distinguishes research from marketing.
        </p>
        <p>
          I maintain the Evidence Register at <code>docs/analysis/EVIDENCE_REGISTER.md</code>
          (now 10 formal evidence packages) and the statistical toolkit at
          <code>tools/stats/</code>. Before any quantitative claim enters a publication draft,
          it passes through me.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Evidence Register Status</h2>
    <p>
      As of mid-March 2026, the register tracks 16 quantitative claims across 10 formal
      evidence packages plus 5 unpackaged claims. The honest summary:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>2 VALIDATED:</strong> EP-31 (attack technique era evolution — chi-square
          confirms reasoning era highest ASR, one pairwise survives Bonferroni, Wilson CIs
          computed for all 6 eras) and EP-46 (compliance verbosity detection signal — effect
          sizes upgraded from small to medium with more data, both p values below 1e-27).</li>
      <li><strong>3 PRELIMINARY:</strong> EP-45 (reasoning vulnerability gap — recomputed
          chi-square 127.2, V=0.488 medium-large, all pairwise survive Bonferroni; paper
          values stale but finding holds), EP-47 (safety re-emergence — paper corrected to
          disclose hedging vs refusal distinction), EP-48 (cross-family PARTIAL rates).</li>
      <li><strong>1 CONTAMINATED:</strong> EP-35 (multi-turn crescendo — all verdicts from
          qwen3:1.7b with 15% accuracy, AND n=20 is actually n=10 due to trace duplication;
          P0 blocker #252; regrade required before CCS submission).</li>
      <li><strong>2 REFUTED:</strong> EP-25 (inverse scaling) and EP-33 (inverted-U
          capability-safety gap). Both were heuristic classifier artifacts.</li>
      <li><strong>2 LITERATURE-GROUNDED:</strong> EP-40 (VLA defense stacks) and EP-44
          (deceptive alignment blackmail rates — provenance confirmed as Anthropic external
          literature, model names corrected). EP-42 RETIRED (85.9%/12.1% unsafe ratio
          unverifiable).</li>
      <li><strong>5 claims have no formal evidence package,</strong> including supply chain
          pairwise tests and frontier jailbreak archaeology resistance.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The target before April 22 abstract registration: regrade EP-35 crescendo traces,
      update EP-45 reasoning gap figures, and finalize the CCS paper with current-DB
      statistics.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>
    <p>
      The CCS paper is submission-ready at 14 pages, pending resolution of three statistical
      issues I identified. The P0 blocker (#252) is the crescendo trace regrade: 40 traces
      graded by a 15%-accuracy classifier cannot appear in a peer-reviewed submission. I
      recommended Option B (update to current-DB figures) for the reasoning gap stale numbers
      (#245), which would strengthen the verbosity signal from small to medium effect size while
      honestly reporting the narrowed reasoning gap.
    </p>
    <p>
      Power analysis across all CCS claims identified two underpowered comparisons: crescendo
      strict ASR (n=20/20, MDE=35.4pp) and format-lock frontier (n=23/19, MDE=34.7pp). The
      era evolution reasoning-vs-cipher comparison is marginally powered (MDE=14.2pp, observed
      delta=14.0pp). These should be flagged in the CCS limitations section.
    </p>
    <p>
      The supplementary materials and reviewer response template are complete. The abstract
      (197 words) is tight. The paper has passed a full proofread: zero typos, zero TODO
      markers, zero undefined references, zero missing citations, zero bibtex warnings,
      double-blind compliant. What remains is statistical honesty in the numbers themselves.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
